suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(GenomicRanges)
  library(epiwraps)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(rGREAT)
})

Download the data

options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.assignment.zip")
unzip("w10.assignment.zip")
list.files()

Prepare the regions and the tracks

tracks <- list.files(pattern="^Creb.*bw$")
regions <- list.files(pattern="^Creb.*bed$")
regions.l <- sapply(regions, rtracklayer::import.bed)
names(regions.l) <- gsub(".bed","",names(regions.l))
regions.l.hq <- lapply(regions.l, function(x) x[x$score>800])

regions.all <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(regions.l.hq)))

Preliminary plot

ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions.all, extend=2000)
set.seed(123)  # to ensure that it gives the same results everytime
nf <- getNormFactors(tracks, useSeqLevels="chr1")
ml2 <- rescaleSignalMatrices(ml, scaleFactors=nf)
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml)

Clustering of relative signals

set.seed(123) # to ensure that it gives the same results everytime
cl.all <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=2:10, scaleRows = TRUE)
ggplot(cl.all$varExplained, aes(k, varExplained)) + geom_line()

set.seed(123)  # to ensure that it gives the same results everytime
# define cluster colors
mycolors <- c("1"="red", "2"="blue", "3"="darkgreen", "4"="black")
# use 4 clusters
cl <- unlist(cl.all$clusters["4"])
# melt all signal matrices into a single dataframe
d <- meltSignals(ml, splitBy=cl)
ggplot(d, aes(position, mean, colour=sample)) + geom_line(size=1.2) + facet_wrap(~split)

plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split = cl, scale_rows = "global", mean_color = mycolors)

GO term enrichment analysis

Find what’s enriched in cluster nr. 3 with respect to the others:

# we first split the regions by cluster:
split_regions <- split(regions.all, cl)

# we send the data to the GREAT server to run an enrichment analysis
job <- submitGreatJob(gr=split_regions[["3"]], bg=regions.all, species="hg38")
res <- getEnrichmentTables(job)

We looked at human-derived ChIPseq peaks of the CREB transcription factor family, which consists of 3 different variants. Clustering of high confidence peak regions according to their signal strength revealed 4 rough TF binding patterns: 1) regions bound by Creb1, 2) regions bound by Creb3, 3) regions bound by Creb3L1 and 4) regions bound by both Creb1 and Creb3L1 but not Creb3. Note that these patterns have overlaps and aren’t clear-cut. We further investigated the regions belonging to the 4th pattern variant for their molecular relevance. A GO term enrichment analysis revealed that regions bound by Creb1 and Creb3L1 but not Creb3 are more commonly associated with specific deubiquitination, the regulation of amide processing and to a lesser degree processes such as cell division, autophagy and nuclear organization.
